Legally.

711
00:44:26,290 --> 00:44:29,543
When I saw you ten years ago,
you loved what you did.

712
00:44:30,085 --> 00:44:32,254
I could feel it all the way in the back row...

713
00:44:32,421 --> 00:44:36,592
...and now you're just a sad,
pathetic shell of what you once were...

714
00:44:36,759 --> 00:44:38,594
...and I don't want any part of it.

715
00:44:41,930 --> 00:44:43,098
What are you doing?

716
00:44:44,600 --> 00:44:46,143
Did I misread the situation?

717
00:44:46,310 --> 00:44:49,104
- Yes. Badly. Just get out.
BURT: Fine.

718
00:44:49,271 --> 00:44:52,107
- I have many options.
JANE: Great.

719
00:44:53,734 --> 00:44:54,818
[SIGHS]

720
00:45:14,838 --> 00:45:16,006
[SIGHS]

721
00:45:20,636 --> 00:45:23,639
[BURT WHIMPERING]

722
00:45:27,518 --> 00:45:29,603
It's so small.

723
00:45:30,479 --> 00:45:33,732
No, I'm saying this bed is the
size a dog would use, or a small child.

724
00:45:33,899 --> 00:45:35,359
I need a bigger bed.

725
00:45:39,363 --> 00:45:42,866
This is your town, Burt.
Tomorrow you take it back.

726
00:45:43,033 --> 00:45:44,660
<i>BURT:
Steve Wynn, please.</i>

727
00:45:44,827 --> 00:45:46,829
Burt Wonderstone.

728
00:45:48,247 --> 00:45:50,249
Well, do you know when he'll be out
of the meeting?

729
00:45:50,416 --> 00:45:51,458
[BIRD TWEETING]

730
00:45:51,625 --> 00:45:52,668
Shh.

731
00:45:52,835 --> 00:45:54,336
I'm trying to talk to Steve Wynn.

732
00:45:54,503 --> 00:45:57,172
Would you tell the Hilton family
Burt Wonderstone called?

733
00:45:57,339 --> 00:45:59,091
Can you have Mr. Trump call me back?

734
00:45:59,258 --> 00:46:01,176
I don't care which Hilton. Nicky will do.

735
00:46:01,343 --> 00:46:05,514
Well, can you have Mrs. Trump call me back?
Mr. Luxor, please.

736
00:46:06,557 --> 00:46:08,058
I don't understand.

737
00:46:08,225 --> 00:46:10,352
<i>DAVID:
Don't think so. I'm not looking for</i> a <i>partner.</i>

738
00:46:10,519 --> 00:46:13,814
I've been a solo act for a million years
and it's going pretty good.

739
00:46:13,981 --> 00:46:16,233
- David, how long have we been friends?
- We're not friends.

740
00:46:16,400 --> 00:46:20,237
Mm-hm. Mm-hm, but if we teamed up,
it could bring your career to the next level.

741
00:46:20,404 --> 00:46:22,865
Well, I have a star
on the Hollywood Walk of Fame.

742
00:46:23,365 --> 00:46:24,491
Imagine this:

743
00:46:24,658 --> 00:46:26,994
"The Incredible Burt & David."

744
00:46:27,870 --> 00:46:28,912
No.

745
00:46:30,622 --> 00:46:31,665
BURT:
All right.

746
00:47:07,075 --> 00:47:10,245
Thank you.
I can make a lot of liquids disappear...

747
00:47:10,412 --> 00:47:13,874
...but nothing makes liquids disappear
better than Bounty paper towels.

748
00:47:14,041 --> 00:47:17,753
They're the quicker picker-upper.
Two rolls for 2.99.

749
00:47:17,920 --> 00:47:19,129
TERRY:
All right, Burt.

750
00:47:19,296 --> 00:47:21,423
- This should do it.
- Thank you, Terry.

751
00:47:21,590 --> 00:47:24,176
If I can do anything else for you,
you have my card.

752
00:47:24,343 --> 00:47:26,220
TERRY: Got it.
- My cell phone number's on there.

753
00:47:26,386 --> 00:47:29,765
TERRY: Uh-huh.
BURT: I will leave my ringer on vibrate.

754
00:47:29,932 --> 00:47:32,726
[CHEERING]

755
00:47:43,612 --> 00:47:46,281
WOMAN: You're the man!
MAN 1: That's right, Steve!

756
00:47:47,115 --> 00:47:50,911
I'm sure you've seen people walk
on red-hot coals.

757
00:47:51,870 --> 00:47:53,956
But I doubt you've seen anyone...

758
00:47:54,122 --> 00:47:55,791
...spend the night...

759
00:47:55,999 --> 00:47:57,960
...on red-hot coals.

760
00:47:58,126 --> 00:48:00,254
MAN 2:
No way!

761
00:48:00,629 --> 00:48:03,382
You know what I say
when I see a bed of...

762
00:48:04,591 --> 00:48:05,926
...red-hot coals?

763
00:48:06,093 --> 00:48:07,844
ALL:
Bring it!

764
00:48:08,637 --> 00:48:10,597
Lucky guess.

765
00:48:14,685 --> 00:48:15,811
[SIZZLING]

766
00:48:15,978 --> 00:48:17,479
[CROWD GASPING]

767
00:48:35,330 --> 00:48:39,501
Now, what you're smelling is not barbecue,
ladies and gentlemen.

768
00:48:39,668 --> 00:48:41,211
It is my actual flesh.

769
00:48:41,378 --> 00:48:43,130
MAN 3:
That's crazy.

770
00:48:43,297 --> 00:48:44,923
See you in the morning!

771
00:48:46,466 --> 00:48:49,595
Somebody get me a wake-up call,
or I'll sleep right through!

772
00:48:52,514 --> 00:48:54,933
[SNORES]

773
00:48:55,100 --> 00:48:56,184
[SCREAMS]

774
00:48:56,351 --> 00:48:57,477
[ALL GASP]

775
00:48:57,644 --> 00:49:00,355
[CONTINUE SCREAMING]

776
00:49:01,356 --> 00:49:03,692
[SNORES]

777
00:49:03,859 --> 00:49:05,193
[SCREAMING]

778
00:49:10,532 --> 00:49:12,534
[SNORES]

779
00:49:15,329 --> 00:49:17,205
[SCREAMING]

780
00:49:19,249 --> 00:49:22,544
[ALL CHEERING]

781
00:50:01,291 --> 00:50:03,001
[CAR HORN HONKS]

782
00:50:08,215 --> 00:50:10,884
MAN:
Under the O, 62.

783
00:50:13,095 --> 00:50:17,432
This is our common room
where you'll be doing the majority of your shit.

784
00:50:17,599 --> 00:50:19,267
What kind of people end up here?

785
00:50:19,434 --> 00:50:21,645
NURSE: Well, most of them were performers
on the Strip.

786
00:50:21,812 --> 00:50:24,398
- Lounge singers, strippers.
- B-1, baby.

787
00:50:24,564 --> 00:50:26,400
NURSE:
Celebrity impersonators.

788
00:50:26,566 --> 00:50:29,903
- So this is where old entertainers go to die.
- Mm-hm.

789
00:50:30,070 --> 00:50:31,947
And some not so old.

790
00:50:32,239 --> 00:50:34,074
MAN:
I-29.

791
00:50:37,911 --> 00:50:40,455
BURT:
Hello. How are you?

792
00:50:42,916 --> 00:50:44,459
What's your name?

793
00:50:44,626 --> 00:50:45,752
- Grace.
- Mm.

794
00:50:46,294 --> 00:50:48,296
Grace, I'm Burt.

795
00:50:48,630 --> 00:50:50,465
That's a lovely bracelet you have.

796
00:50:50,632 --> 00:50:52,884
May I see that for a minute?

797
00:50:56,263 --> 00:50:58,056
Take your time.

798
00:51:00,642 --> 00:51:02,436
[SIGHS]

799
00:51:03,353 --> 00:51:05,564
The clasp is in the back.

800
00:51:06,440 --> 00:51:09,067
Yes. Oh, there we go.

801
00:51:09,609 --> 00:51:11,319
Oh. Thank you.

802
00:51:11,486 --> 00:51:14,197
Now, watch this.

803
00:51:16,950 --> 00:51:19,286
Aah! Where did it go?

804
00:51:19,453 --> 00:51:21,455
I don't know.

805
00:51:21,872 --> 00:51:25,167
My granddaughter gave that to me.

806
00:51:25,625 --> 00:51:28,336
What have you done? Oh.

807
00:51:28,503 --> 00:51:30,797
No. It's right here.

808
00:51:30,964 --> 00:51:34,217
I have it. I have it. I have it. It's right here.

809
00:51:34,384 --> 00:51:35,552
I'm a magician.

810
00:51:35,719 --> 00:51:36,762
[WOMAN SOBBING]

811
00:51:36,928 --> 00:51:39,139
I should have explained that to you earlier.

812
00:51:39,306 --> 00:51:40,849
Oh, my God.

813
00:51:41,016 --> 00:51:42,851
[CONTINUES SOBBING]

814
00:51:43,727 --> 00:51:45,353
It's all right.

815
00:51:47,522 --> 00:51:51,777
Sir, if you would do me a kindness
and select one card only from this deck.

816
00:51:51,943 --> 00:51:53,487
MAN:
He's forcing it on you.

817
00:51:54,529 --> 00:51:58,158
- Show the card to others. Do not show me.
MAN: Don't do it. He's a hack.

818
00:51:58,325 --> 00:51:59,367
WOMAN:
Shh.

819
00:51:59,868 --> 00:52:02,954
Please put the card back in the deck.
Do not show me the card.

820
00:52:04,206 --> 00:52:06,750
- I will out the deck once--
MAN: He already knows the card.

821
00:52:06,917 --> 00:52:08,710
- Is this your card?
- No.

822
00:52:08,877 --> 00:52:11,379
- Really? Hmm. That's odd.
MAN: It's part of the bit.

823
00:52:11,546 --> 00:52:14,925
He's gonna guess wrong twice
and then tell you the card's in your pocket.

824
00:52:15,091 --> 00:52:16,885
Thank you, sir, for ruining the trick.

825
00:52:17,052 --> 00:52:19,262
MAN:
Well, thank you for being so terrible.

826
00:52:28,021 --> 00:52:30,440
Hey, pal. Cardigan.

827
00:52:31,191 --> 00:52:34,569
- What's your problem?
- I don't have a problem, but you do.

828
00:52:34,736 --> 00:52:37,155
- Oh.
- Your Zarrow Shuffle is sloppy...

829
00:52:37,322 --> 00:52:39,866
...your lips move
when you do the Elmsley Count...

830
00:52:40,033 --> 00:52:43,370
...and your patter is boring and sad.
You wanna try and dazzle people...

831
00:52:43,537 --> 00:52:45,539
...not put them to sleep, for God's sakes.

832
00:52:45,705 --> 00:52:46,915
Really? What else?

833
00:52:47,082 --> 00:52:50,460
People want to think what they're seeing
is real magic, not a magic show.

834
00:52:50,627 --> 00:52:53,713
If you don't believe what you're doing,
how are they gonna believe?

835
00:52:53,880 --> 00:52:55,423
You got no joy in you, son.

836
00:52:55,590 --> 00:52:56,800
You got no passion.

837
00:52:56,967 --> 00:53:00,554
You may have seen these tricks
a thousand times before, but they haven't.

838
00:53:05,392 --> 00:53:06,434
Oh, my God.

839
00:53:09,104 --> 00:53:10,146
You're Rance Holloway.

840
00:53:11,731 --> 00:53:13,066
[BURT GASPS]

841
00:53:13,233 --> 00:53:14,526
<i>L.</i>

842
00:53:15,235 --> 00:53:19,114
I had your magic kit as a kid.
You're the reason I became a magician.

843
00:53:19,281 --> 00:53:20,949
I'll give you your money back.

844
00:53:21,992 --> 00:53:24,160
Well, I don't think you understand.

845
00:53:24,494 --> 00:53:26,413
I am Burt Wonderstone.

846
00:53:26,621 --> 00:53:29,958
I gather from that I'm supposed
to pass out now'?

847
00:53:30,625 --> 00:53:33,712
Well, I headlined at Bally's
for the last ten years.

848
00:53:34,170 --> 00:53:35,338
I'm very, very famous.

849
00:53:36,131 --> 00:53:39,593
Well, I quit the business
and I don't read the trades...

850
00:53:39,759 --> 00:53:41,428
...and I'm late for my coma.

851
00:53:41,595 --> 00:53:44,973
Well, perhaps we could just talk
for a couple of minutes?

852
00:53:45,807 --> 00:53:47,434
Bye.

853
00:53:56,651 --> 00:53:58,653
[RANCE LAUGHING]

854
00:54:09,956 --> 00:54:11,666
<i>COMMENTATOR [ON TV]:
This could win it!</i>

855
00:54:11,833 --> 00:54:13,835
ANNOUNCER [ON TV]:
Tonight on The Brain Rapist:

856
00:54:14,002 --> 00:54:15,462
<i>Will there be blood?</i>

857
00:54:17,339 --> 00:54:19,341
<i>And that brings us to our profile tonight.</i>

858
00:54:19,507 --> 00:54:23,011
<i>A man who left behind the glitz and glamour
of Las Vegas stardom...</i>

859
00:54:23,178 --> 00:54:25,305
...to <i>follow</i> a <i>different path.</i>

860
00:54:25,472 --> 00:54:27,474
<i>His name is Anton Marvelton.</i>

861
00:54:34,522 --> 00:54:38,401
<i>I started Operation Presto! because I saw
how much suffering there was in the world.</i>

862
00:54:38,568 --> 00:54:43,907
<i>I go to places where the children
have neither food nor clean water...</i>

863
00:54:45,158 --> 00:54:46,493
<i>...and I give them magic.</i>

864
00:54:47,869 --> 00:54:50,372
<i>And do you also give them food
and clean water?</i>

865
00:54:52,207 --> 00:54:55,585
<i>Well, no. I'm a magician. I bring magic.</i>

866
00:54:56,252 --> 00:54:59,005
<i>Hi, kids! Here you go.</i>

867
00:54:59,172 --> 00:55:00,840
<i>That's for you.</i>

868
00:55:01,007 --> 00:55:02,884
<i>Here you go, young man.</i>

869
00:55:03,051 --> 00:55:04,427
<i>And for you.</i>

870
00:55:04,594 --> 00:55:06,554
<i>Let's see that smile. Ha-ha-ha.</i>

871
00:55:06,721 --> 00:55:09,182
<i>Don't worry, I have plenty for everybody.</i>

872
00:55:09,349 --> 00:55:10,725
<i>What have we here?</i>

873
00:55:10,892 --> 00:55:12,435
<i>Presto! Ha-ha-ha.</i>

874
00:55:12,936 --> 00:55:14,396
<i>That's not all.</i>

875
00:55:14,562 --> 00:55:16,898
<i>Hey, here you go.</i>

876
00:55:17,065 --> 00:55:18,858
<i>How about that?</i>

877
00:55:20,276 --> 00:55:21,861
[SPEAKS IN SPANISH]

878
00:55:22,028 --> 00:55:23,279
<i>There you are.</i>

879
00:55:23,446 --> 00:55:26,074
<i>That's for you, and you.</i>

880
00:55:26,241 --> 00:55:30,286
<i>They should have fresh rabbits
to practice magic with, don't you agree?</i>

881
00:55:30,787 --> 00:55:33,540
<i>This area of the world is so troubled.</i>

882
00:55:33,707 --> 00:55:37,002
<i>Not only is there rampant poverty
and no fresh water...</i>

883
00:55:37,168 --> 00:55:41,589
<i>...but the locals are also hooked
on a powerful drug called kratom leaf.</i>

884
00:55:41,756 --> 00:55:43,883
<i>It knocks them unconscious for an hour.</i>

885
00:55:44,050 --> 00:55:47,846
<i>So I'm trying to get them off the kratom
and hooked on magic instead.</i>

886
00:55:48,013 --> 00:55:50,682
<i>Now, you're here in part
because you had a falling-out...</i>

887
00:55:50,849 --> 00:55:54,394
<i>...with your longtime magic partner
and best friend, Burt Wonderstone.</i>

888
00:55:55,228 --> 00:55:56,938
<i>ANTON:
He was my best friend.</i>

889
00:55:57,105 --> 00:55:58,732
<i>He was like a brother to me.</i>

890
00:55:58,898 --> 00:56:01,901
<i>And I'll always be grateful to him
for showing me my first trick.</i>

891
00:56:02,402 --> 00:56:04,112
INTERVIEWER:
Do you remember what that was?

892
00:56:04,446 --> 00:56:05,947
<i>A disappearing handkerchief.</i>

893
00:56:06,114 --> 00:56:09,075
<i>It's the first trick everyone learns,
but I'll tell you what.</i>

894
00:56:09,242 --> 00:56:11,119
<i>When Burt did it that day...</i>

895
00:56:11,286 --> 00:56:13,663
<i>...it really blew my mind.</i>

896
00:56:24,174 --> 00:56:27,302
Rance, let's do some tricks.

897
00:56:28,053 --> 00:56:29,429
Rance.

898
00:56:29,596 --> 00:56:31,222
Aah! Jeez!

899
00:56:31,389 --> 00:56:32,474
What are you doing here?

900
00:56:32,640 --> 00:56:34,976
- I wanna do tricks.
- What are you doing in my room?

901
00:56:35,143 --> 00:56:37,479
- Look what I brought. Remember that?
- I don't care.

902
00:56:37,645 --> 00:56:40,315
I thought that we could do some tricks
together.

903
00:56:40,482 --> 00:56:43,485
The whole point of the kit was so
that you could do the tricks without me.

904
00:56:43,651 --> 00:56:45,987
Ooh! The dangling knot.

905
00:56:46,154 --> 00:56:48,323
And the rings. Remember the rings?

906
00:56:48,490 --> 00:56:50,825
How do these work again?

907
00:56:52,994 --> 00:56:57,332
If I show you how to do the rings,
will you leave me alone?

908
00:56:57,499 --> 00:56:59,042
We'll see.

909
00:56:59,918 --> 00:57:01,503
Ugh.

910
00:57:04,047 --> 00:57:07,258
Slide that one out, you need
to get the fingers, and there.

911
00:57:07,425 --> 00:57:09,677
No good. I can see the corner of the card.

912
00:57:09,844 --> 00:57:11,846
- Really?
- Yeah.

913
00:57:13,681 --> 00:57:15,683
- There?
- Yeah. Squeeze your fingers tighter.

914
00:57:15,850 --> 00:57:17,685
- All right.
- Tighter!

915
00:57:19,521 --> 00:57:23,191
How in the hell did you ever perform
on a Las Vegas stage?

916
00:57:23,358 --> 00:57:28,029
I didn't do very many card tricks.
I mostly worked with big giant props.

917
00:57:28,196 --> 00:57:29,864
Big giant props.

918
00:57:32,617 --> 00:57:34,369
Do you mind if I ask you something?

919
00:57:34,536 --> 00:57:36,371
If you feel you should.

920
00:57:37,163 --> 00:57:40,083
What happened? I mean,
one day you were headlining at Bally's...

921
00:57:40,250 --> 00:57:42,585
...the next day you just disappeared.

922
00:57:43,837 --> 00:57:45,880
Pass me the salt.

923
00:57:48,883 --> 00:57:51,719
Do you remember
why you became a magician?

924
00:57:52,220 --> 00:57:54,222
Because everybody loves a magician.

925
00:57:54,389 --> 00:57:56,015
Right.

926
00:58:01,896 --> 00:58:03,356
H ow--?

927
00:58:03,523 --> 00:58:04,607
How'd--?

928
00:58:05,900 --> 00:58:07,402
How'd--?

929
00:58:10,238 --> 00:58:11,948
What you're feeling right now...

930
00:58:12,115 --> 00:58:15,243
...that sense of awe,
that sense of wonderment...

931
00:58:15,410 --> 00:58:19,038
...that sense that anything
in the universe is possible?

932
00:58:19,664 --> 00:58:21,708
That's why you became a magician.

933
00:58:22,250 --> 00:58:24,878
That's why I became a magician.

934
00:58:25,253 --> 00:58:28,089
- That, and the women.
- That, and the women.

935
00:58:28,423 --> 00:58:30,758
So why did you just walk away?

936
00:58:31,676 --> 00:58:36,389
I was on a stage one day and,
all of a sudden, it had become rote...

937
00:58:36,598 --> 00:58:38,016
...it'd become mechanical...

938
00:58:38,183 --> 00:58:41,269
...and I didn't like that feeling.

939
00:58:41,769 --> 00:58:43,771
So I walked away and I never looked back.

940
00:58:45,481 --> 00:58:46,941
<i>Hmm.</i>

941
00:58:51,613 --> 00:58:55,617
Honestly, how did you do that
with the bird?

942
00:58:58,328 --> 00:59:01,164
It's partially deboned.

943
00:59:23,186 --> 00:59:25,480
[CELL PHONE RINGS]

944
00:59:27,148 --> 00:59:28,608
Hello?

945
00:59:31,152 --> 00:59:33,029
I'll be right there.

946
00:59:33,196 --> 00:59:34,656
DOUG:
Burt! Burt, how are you?

947
00:59:34,822 --> 00:59:36,616
- Doug.
- Come here.

948
00:59:37,325 --> 00:59:39,786
- How you holding up?
BURT: Very well, very well.

949
00:59:39,953 --> 00:59:41,454
